  "text": "These anti-inflammatory compounds are, however, bound and are not bioavailable as shown in Table 2 . Therefore, fermenting them with L. mesenteroides enabled the release of pectolinarin and pectolinarigenin. This accounts for the high pectolinarin and pectolinarigenin contents in fermented samples relative to the unfermented samples containing C. setidens Nakai. Fermentation of garlic also significantly increased the levels of SAC from 1.8 ± 0.1 mg/g to 4.43 ± 0.67 mg/g (Table 4 ). Furthermore, phenolic and flavonoid compounds generally increased with fermentation (Table 3) . Our results agree with an earlier study in which the phenolic content of fermented okra seeds increased significantly relative to unfermented seeds [CITATION_1] . This might be due to the ability of the LAB enzymes to hydrolyze the samples to release bound phenolic and flavonoid compounds during the fermentation process.",
